The electrochemical performance of B-TiO2 NCs and W-TiO2 NCs were investigated using lithium half-cells. CV plots at a scan rate of 0.2 mV s−1 are shown in Fig. 5
                        a, the main pair of peaks located at near 1.66/2.08 V can be assigned to Li insertion/extraction into anatase TiO2 [4]. It is clear that the electrochemical polarization of B-TiO2 NCs electrode is lower than that of the W-TiO2 NCs electrode [4]. The decrease of the electrochemical polarization by the Ti3+ defects results from the increase of the electrical conductivity, which increases the transportation rate of electrons during the electrochemical reactions. Furthermore, CV curves display a broad feature, which are characteristic of surface/interfacial pseudocapacitive Li+ storage contributed from Ti3+ defects in B-TiO2 NCs and the disordered surface layers with high surface area [34,35]. Fig. 5b exhibits the galvanostatic charge/discharge curves of the B-TiO2 NCs and W-TiO2 NCs electrodes at a rate of 0.5 C. The discharge curves of these two electrodes possess similar slope region (<1.80 V), which are associated with the fast surface/interfacial pseudocapacitive Li+ intercalation at the surface/interfacial of these structured materials [34,35]. Additionally, it is found that the ratios of capacitive charge capacity for the B-TiO2 NCs and the W-TiO2 NCs electrodes are up to 73.3% and 68.9%, respectively, which explain the excellent rate capability of these electrodes. Fig. 5c shows the rate capability of the B-TiO2 NCs and the W-TiO2 NCs electrodes. The B-TiO2 NCs electrode can deliver a specific capacity of 271, 262, 240, 213, 186 and 159 mAh g−1 at rates of 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10 and 20 C (1 C = 168 mA g−1), respectively. Taking the black TiO2 reported recently for comparison (Table 1
                        ), the B-TiO2 NCs reported here displays high capacity and excellent rate capability for LIB anodes, which is likely to be associated with the small particle size of black TiO2 nanocrystals (ca. 6 nm) which can greatly increase lithium storage capacity and Li-ion solid solubility owing to the favorable phase boundary energetics [36]. While for the W-TiO2 NCs electrode, it can only deliver specific capacities of 201, 179, 158, 135, 98 and 74 mAh g−1 at the same rates owing to high electrochemical polarization. Fig. 5d compares the cycling performance of the B-TiO2 NCs and the W-TiO2 NCs electrodes at 0.5 C. It is apparent that the reversible capacity of the B-TiO2 NCs electrode is about 271 mAh g−1, much higher than that of the W-TiO2 NCs one (201 mAh g−1). In addition, the retention ratio of the B-TiO2 NCs electrode after 200 cycles (98.5%) is much higher than that of W-TiO2 NCs electrode (93.7%), indicating the excellent cycling performance of the B-TiO2 NCs electrode.
